answers.body_markdown:
An enum in Java is an subclass of type `Enum`. An enum in Java is not of type `String`.

When you call `e.name()`, **you get a `String`** rather than an enum object. You pass that as the key to your map. So you have a map of strings to `randomstuff`, not a map of enum to `randomstuff`.

Let&#39;s get concrete with a realistic example. Here we map an enum object of [`java.time.DayOfWeek`][1] to a `Person` object whose class we define elsewhere. The idea here is that for the upcoming week we assign a particular person to each day&#39;s work shift. 

Define our three workers.

    Person alice = new Person( &quot;Alice&quot; );
    Person bob = new Person( &quot;Bob&quot; );
    Person carol = new Person( &quot;Carol&quot; );

Define a [`Map`][2] of each day to a person. 

    Map &lt; DayOfWeek, Person &gt; workWeek = new EnumMap &lt;&gt;( DayOfWeek.class );

Notice in the code above that we use the [`EnumMap`][3] class. This class is highly optimized to work with enum objects, running very fast while taking up very little memory. If your key is an enum, always use `EnumMap` rather than `HashMap`. 

Here is a reminder of the various `Map` implementations bundled with Java 11.

[![Java map to Maps.png][4]][4]

Assign a person for each day of the week.

    workWeek.put( DayOfWeek.MONDAY , bob );
    workWeek.put( DayOfWeek.TUESDAY , carol );
    workWeek.put( DayOfWeek.WEDNESDAY , carol );
    workWeek.put( DayOfWeek.THURSDAY , alice );
    workWeek.put( DayOfWeek.FRIDAY , alice );
    workWeek.put( DayOfWeek.SATURDAY , bob );
    workWeek.put( DayOfWeek.SUNDAY , alice );

Dump to console.

    System.out.println( &quot;workweek: &quot; + workWeek );

&gt;workweek: {MONDAY=Person{ name=&#39;Bob&#39; }, TUESDAY=Person{ name=&#39;Carol&#39; }, WEDNESDAY=Person{ name=&#39;Carol&#39; }, THURSDAY=Person{ name=&#39;Alice&#39; }, FRIDAY=Person{ name=&#39;Alice&#39; }, SATURDAY=Person{ name=&#39;Bob&#39; }, SUNDAY=Person{ name=&#39;Alice&#39; }}

Notice how nowhere in our mapping did we use a `String`. We never said `&quot;Monday&quot;` nor `&quot;monday&quot;`. We never called `DayOfWeek.MONDAY.name()`.

By the way, if you do need some text to represent the day-of-week, do not call `.name`. To automatically localize, call [`DayOfWeek::getDisplayName`][5]. When writing your own enums, I suggest you too add something like a `getDisplayName` method (even if for only a single language). 

The [`Enum::name`][6] method really should *not* be called in most situations. The main point of inventing the sophisticated enum facility in Java is to *not* depend on such mere strings (or mere integers) that tend to make our code brittle and difficult to read/debug.


  [1]: https://docs.oracle.com/en/java/javase/11/docs/api/java.base/java/time/DayOfWeek.html
  [2]: https://docs.oracle.com/en/java/javase/11/docs/api/java.base/java/util/Map.html
  [3]: https://docs.oracle.com/en/java/javase/11/docs/api/java.base/java/util/EnumMap.html
  [4]: https://i.stack.imgur.com/4k7X7.png
  [5]: https://docs.oracle.com/en/java/javase/11/docs/api/java.base/java/time/DayOfWeek.html#getDisplayName(java.time.format.TextStyle,java.util.Locale)
  [6]: https://docs.oracle.com/en/java/javase/11/docs/api/java.base/java/lang/Enum.html#name()

